ays of thinking and acting? Recent historiography has almost completely ignored the ways in which death created such immense social change in China. Now, Scythe and the City corrects this problem. Christian Henriot's pioneering and original study of Shanghai between 1865 and 1965 offers new insights into this crucial aspect of modern society in a global commercial hub and guides readers through this tumultuous era that radically redefined the Chinese relationship with death.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aDeathxSocial aspectszChinazShanghaixHistoryy19th century. 0aDeathxSocial aspectszChinazShanghaixHistoryy20th century. 4aChina. 4aShanghai. 4abody. 4acity. 4adeath. 4afuneral. 4apopulation. 4apower. 4aritual. 4aurban. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804798747zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798747423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804798747.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles